    en: "A Rochester tenant on a month-to-month lease for 28 months received a notice from her landlord saying her tenancy was terminated and she had 30 days to vacate. RPL 232-a requires 90 days notice for a tenancy of more than 2 years, so 30 days was not enough. The tenant did not move. The landlord filed a holdover petition. With Legal Aid representation, the tenant filed an answer raising the inadequate notice defense and attaching her rent receipts proving the 28-month tenancy. The court dismissed the petition without prejudice. The landlord could re-serve a proper 90-day notice and refile after the new period expired. By the time of dismissal, the tenant had used the time to find new housing and moved out voluntarily without a judgment on her record."
